llinois johnson earned a bachelor of arts in history at the university of illinois in  he also received a masters in public administration from princeton university in new jersey in  johnson then moved to washington dc where he worked for both the corporation for public broadcasting and the national urban league in  johnson became the vice president of governmental relations for the national cable television association ncta an organization comprised of various cable television companies johnson’s work with ncta inspired him to develop television programming that was dedicated to african american viewers who at that time were unrecognized as a target audience group he initially borrowed  from the president of the ncta tom wheeler to fund his plan of gaining a black viewership in television later he persuaded john malone the president of telecommunications inc to invest  in the project bet first aired in january  and its content primarily consisted of black films from the s and s later with the development of music television mtv music videos became ingrained in the popular media and bet promoted black rhythm and blues and hip hop artists even though bet only aired for a few hours each day in its early years it quickly developed into an influential medium for african american selfexpression and racial pride within american popular culture after increasing air time to  hours a day bet soon claimed an audience of over  million households  it had also grown large enough to be listed on the new york stock exchange in  although bet thrived in the s by expanding its viewership and product line johnson decided to take the company private in  in  he sold bet to viacom for  billion making johnson the first black billionaire he retained his position as the ceo of bet until  and afterward formed the robert l johnson companies a conglomerate of firms that worked in financial services hospitality real estate film production professional sports gaming and recording industries in  johnson purchased ownership of the charlotte bobcats a north carolina basketball team and the following year he  launched a regional sports and entertainment television network today he is most famous for his promotion and dissemination of late twentieth century forms of black cultural expression sourcesdavid hatchett “the crisis interview robert johnson” the crisis new york october   vol  no  p  httpwwwbiographycompeoplerobertljohnson httpwwwreferenceforbusinesscombiographyfljohnsonrobertlhtml httpwwwzeromillioncomentrepreneurshipstoriesrobertjohnsonhtml contributor zenz cassandra independent historian entry categories th century athletes black recording industry business illinois media radiotvprint men mississippi new jersey north carolina people radiotelevision raphip hop rhythm  blues theatrefilmtv urban league washington dc copyright   blackpastorg v  blackpastblackpastorg  your donations help us to grow  we welcome your suggestions  mission statement blackpastorg is an independent nonprofit corporation c it has no affiliation with the university of washington blackpastorg is supported in part by a grant from humanities washington a statewide nonprofit organization supported by the national endowment for the humanities the state of washington and contributions from individuals and foundations african american history  the black past remembered and reclaimed an online reference guide to african american history home main featuresaah index page aaw index page gah index page perspective articles black history month blackpastorg the united states blackpastorg and the world digital archives genealogy black national anthem barack obama page  african american firsts major black office holders lgbtq page users guide site map special featuresblacks and the lds church the mentoring page preserving king county’s african american history african american ambassadors speakers bureau african and west indian capital cities dever memorial page on afrobritons historic african a